Hi @qlik-user , what steps did you take to update the SSE?

To upgrade to a new version you'll need to:
- Extract the [new release](qlik-py-env)
- If installing the SSE at the same location as a previous version, delete* the `qlik-py-env` directory.
- Run the `Qlik-Py-Init.bat` file as an administrator

*If you have trained models using the scikit-learn functions, you can take a backup of the `qlik-py-env/models` directory and copy it back after the upgrade. However, you may need to retrain the models if certain packages (`joblib`) have been updated in the release.

Thanks for your fast response.

I did exactly this, but keep getting this error. :/
Can you try again and get the full log from `Qlik-Py-Init.bat`. There must have been an error around where `pystan` or `fbprophet` are being installed. Also what version of Python are you using?

After this I have to install 
grpcio==1.7.3
and
pandas==0.22.0

and after that the error message "fbprophet" appears.

I see an error in the log that mean's the virtual environment is not being activated:

```
Activating the virtual environment...

Parameterformat falsch - 850.
```

Some googling shows that this is a Python issue with German/ Swiss Windows: 
https://github.com/python/cpython/pull/10696?

This is fixed in later versions of Python, but unfortunately those versions are incompatible with some packages used in this SSE. So the solution will be to manually update `activate.bat` with the fix.

So first, just run the initialization up to the point where we create the virtual environment and copy the SSE files:
```
@echo off
echo Setting up the Python virtual environment... & echo.
python -m venv "%~dp0\qlik-py-env"
echo.
echo Copying project files to the new directory... & echo.
xcopy /E /I "%~dp0\generated" "%~dp0\qlik-py-env\generated"
xcopy /E /I "%~dp0\core" "%~dp0\qlik-py-env\core"
echo.
```

Then navigate to `qlik-py-env\Scripts` and update the `activate.bat` file with fix [8321](https://github.com/python/cpython/pull/8321/files). I'm not sure if you'll need the related fix [10295](https://github.com/python/cpython/pull/10295/files) as well.

Then you can run the rest of the script from `Qlik-Py-Init.bat`.

Another option may be to just try the powershell script instead of the batch file, i.e. use `Qlik-Py-Init.ps1`. It sounds like the bug only applies to `activate.bat`. Initializing via powershell uses `activate.ps1` so perhaps won't have this issue.
